HEADWORD: Catechise
<hw>Cat"e*chise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Catechised</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Catechising</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>catechizare</ets>, Gr. <?/, equiv. to <?/ to resound, sound a thing
into one's ears, impress it upon one by word of mouth; <?/ + <?/ to
sound, <?/ a sound.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To instruct by asking questions, receiving answers,
and offering explanations and corrections, -- esp. in regard to points
of religious faith.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To question or interrogate; to examine or try by
questions; -- sometimes with a view to reproof, by eliciting from a
person answers which condemn his own conduct.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 227 --></p>

<p><ent>Catechiser</ent>⟦br⟧
